The fact that nearly 50% of the viruses for which IFN antagonists have been identified interfere with multiple steps of the IFN response (Figure 1
), exemplifies the necessity for viruses to successfully circumvent the IFN response. Moreover, approximately one third of the viruses encode an antagonist that interferes with more than one step of the IFN response system (Figure 2, Figure 3
), underpinning the pleiotropic nature of viral proteins.
